b000-q-cleanup-entry.oracle:
Putting cleanup logic in an exit ability is unreliable when a walker might disengage partway through traversal because exit abilities are deferred and may not run if `disengage` is called. Specifically:

- Exit abilities execute in a post-order manner after visiting all descendants.
- If the walker calls `disengage`, it immediately stops traversal and skips the remaining nodes, including the deferred exit abilities.
- This means cleanup logic in exit abilities might never execute if disengage interrupts traversal early.

The recommended alternative is to place cleanup logic in an entry ability instead of an exit ability. Entry abilities run immediately when entering a node and will run even if the walker disengages later. This ensures cleanup code reliably executes regardless of early termination.

### Why it matters
- Reliable cleanup is critical to maintain consistent state and avoid resource leaks or incomplete processing.
- Understanding walker traversal semantics (entry abilities run immediately, exit abilities are deferred) helps design robust walkers.

### Step-by-step breakdown
- `disengage`: Stops the walker immediately, preventing further node visits and skipping deferred exit abilities.
- `exit ability`: Runs after all child nodes are visited (deferred execution).
- `entry ability`: Runs immediately upon node visit.

### Example before (unreliable cleanup in exit ability)
```jac
walker MyWalker {
    can process with MyNode entry {
