b002-q-root-vs-node-spawn.base:
The difference between spawning a walker on root versus a specific node relates to **where in the DOM tree** the walker is initialized and how it traverses content.

## Spawning on Root vs Specific Node

### Spawning on Root
```javascript
// Creates walker starting from document root
const walker = document.createTreeWalker(
  document.body, // root node
  NodeFilter.SHOW_ALL,
  null
);
```

### Spawning on Specific Node
```javascript
// Creates walker starting from a specific element
const specificElement = document.getElementById('myDiv');
const walker = document.createTreeWalker(
  specificElement, // specific node as root
  NodeFilter.SHOW_ALL,
  null
);
```

## Key Differences

| Aspect | Root Spawning | Specific Node Spawning |
|--------|---------------|----------------------|
| **Scope** | Entire document | Subtree only |
| **Performance** | Slower (traverses whole DOM) | Faster (limited scope) |
| **Memory** | Higher (more nodes) | Lower (fewer nodes) |
| **Flexibility** | Less control | More targeted |

## When to Use Specific Node Spawning

### 1. **Targeted Content Processing**
```javascript
// Process only a specific section
const contentDiv = document.querySelector('.article-content');
const walker = document.createTreeWalker(
  contentDiv,
  NodeFilter.SHOW_TEXT,
  null
);

// Only processes text

