b002-q-single-file-fullstack.oracle:
In a single-file fullstack Jac app, client-side code accesses and invokes server-side walkers defined in the same file by using the `sv import` statement to import the server-side walkers into the client code. Then, the client code "spawns" these walkers on the root node to call them and get results.

### Why this matters
- This pattern allows you to write fullstack apps in one Jac file, simplifying development.
- The compiler automatically separates client and server code, handling the network communication.
- The client can call server logic transparently without manual REST API code.

### Step-by-step breakdown

- **`sv import from <file> { Walker1, Walker2, ... }`**  
  This imports server-side walkers into client code. The `sv` prefix marks the import as server-side, so the compiler keeps it as a server reference.

- **`root spawn WalkerName(params)`**  
  This creates and runs a walker starting at the root node. The walker executes on the server.

- **`result.reports`**  
  The walker reports typed objects. The client receives these as the result with full field access.

### Declaration example (server side walkers)

```jac
walker AddTask {
    has title: str,
        reports: list[Task] = [];

    can add with Root entry {
        new_task = create Task(title=self.title, done=false);
        report new_task;
    }
}
```

### Usage example (client side code)

```jac
sv import from main {
    AddTask
}

async fn addNewTask(task_title: str) {
    result = root spawn AddTask(title=task_title);
    new_task = result.reports[0];
    print(new_task.title);
}
```

### Summary
- Client imports server walkers with `sv import`
- Client spawns walkers with `root spawn Walker(params)`
- Walkers run on server and return typed reports to client

This enables seamless client-server communication in a single-file Jac app.

